Ok, this was actually a bug and it is now fixed in the master branch. You'll still need to change the `thead` into an info-only tbody

```html
<tbody class="tablesorter-infoOnly headers"></tbody>
```

Then clone the rendered header html and bind the sort events ([demo](http://jsfiddle.net/Mottie/856bzzeL/781/)):

```js
$(function () {
	$( 'table' ).tablesorter({
		theme: 'blue',
		widgets: [ 'zebra', 'columns' ],
		initialized: function ( table ) {
			var c = table.config,
			$extraHeaders = c.$table.children( 'tbody.headers' );
			// make a copy of the rendered headers
			$extraHeaders.html( c.$table.children( 'thead' ).html() );
			// make extra headers clickable
			$.tablesorter.bindEvents( table, $extraHeaders );
		}
	});
});
```

But as you can see in that demo, it will work on any number of extra headers.

Hi @aetna-wsa!

Here is one method of doing it ([demo](http://jsfiddle.net/Mottie/856bzzeL/720/)):
* Wrap the table with a `div`.
* Add the theme class to the table, in this case we'll use `"tablesorter-blue"`

    ```html
    <div class="wrapper loading">
        <table class="tablesorter-blue">...</table>
    </div>
    ```
* Add some css to cover the entire table (overlay) and add a loading indicator

    ```css
    .wrapper {
      position: relative;
    }
    .loading:before {
      content: '';
      display: block;
      width: 100%;
      height: 100%;
      position: absolute;
      top: 0;
      left: 0;
      bottom: 0;
      right: 0;
      z-index: 100;
      background: rgba(0,0,0,0.3) center center no-repeat url('data:image/gif;base64,
    ```

* Once you finish loading the content, then initialize tablesorter & in the `initialized` callback, remove the overlay - the demo doesn't do this because it's not loading content.

    ```js
    $('table').tablesorter({
        theme: 'blue',
        initialized: function(){
            $('.wrapper').removeClass('loading');
        }
    });
    ```

