@rtibbles We're hiding for good reason. If we show the score before the exam completes, the score is still tentative and not finalized. The teacher probably knows this and will understand that there probably isn't a real reason for them to stare consistently at fluctuating scores, because, well, they're fluctuating and won't be set in stone until the exam ends. 

Instead, what's the real use of this exam view? Well, probably to get a quick glimpse at how many students finished, and who's still in progress. The more easily we can create a visual separation between the two, the better. It probably wouldn't help if there were percentages everywhere. If there were, teachers would be forced to check the status column instead of the percent column, which is even more reading. The purpose of the % column would be defeated.

The sacrifice overall makes for a more readable experience IMO.

